e region and overestimated the regimes' strategic capabilities to manage these changes. She argues that the Arab Spring was fifteen years in the making, gradually inflamed by growing popular demand—and expectation—for free expression, by top-down restrictions on citizens' political rights, and by the failure of the region's autocrats to follow through on liberalizing reforms they had promised more than a decade earlier.An incisive account of events whose ramifications are still unfolding, Roots of the Arab Spring captures the tectonic shifts in the region that led to the first major political upheaval of the twenty-first century.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aArab Spring, 2010-. 0aAuthoritarianismzArab countries ty21st century. 0aAuthoritarianismzArab countriesy20th century. 0aProtest movementszArab countriesy20th century. 0aProtest movementszArab countriesy21st century. 4aPublic Policy. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh  aPolitical Science.  aPublic Policy.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Law & Political Sciencez978311041352608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220841240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812208412423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780812208412/original  a978-3-11-041345-8  Penn Press eBook Package Complete Collection  a978-3-11-041352-6  Penn Press eBook Package Law & Political Science  a978-3-11-045954-8  University of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEB